176
00:09:38,911 --> 00:09:39,579
Right?

177
00:09:39,579 --> 00:09:43,416
Or are there more jobs to process,
whatever the case may be,

178
00:09:43,708 --> 00:09:48,045
when do I shut down,
these go routines or these workers?

179
00:09:48,337 --> 00:09:49,714
When do I keep them up?

180
00:09:49,714 --> 00:09:53,342
Do I only process one thing
and then and then shut them down?

181
00:09:53,843 --> 00:09:57,722
So I need to make sure that I set up
these contexts appropriately.

182
00:09:57,722 --> 00:10:01,976
Otherwise I can get, coroutines
that link leak and keep doing

183
00:10:01,976 --> 00:10:05,813
useless work and just, 
chewing up, resources that are valuable.

184
00:10:07,064 --> 00:10:07,523
Right.

185
00:10:07,523 --> 00:10:12,737
So when do I use go and when do I use,
these go routine concepts

186
00:10:13,070 --> 00:10:16,032
when I need to make independent
IO calls per request.

187
00:10:16,032 --> 00:10:18,117
This is a good way to go, right?

188
00:10:18,117 --> 00:10:21,704
If I have background processing
with, like, I can control

189
00:10:21,746 --> 00:10:24,290
with, concurrency here.

190
00:10:24,290 --> 00:10:27,335
And when I have services that need,
like robust timeout

191
00:10:27,335 --> 00:10:31,255
and cancellation of behavior,
go is a great place to go.

192
00:10:31,255 --> 00:10:36,677
That's why we're seeing more people use,
go for gateways and aggregation.

193
00:10:36,677 --> 00:10:39,680
Things in like that. All right.

194
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:43,059
Here are some trade offs and pitfalls
you need to work through as an architect.

195
00:10:44,101 --> 00:10:48,230
The benefit and we've talked about this
with like Node.js as well.

196
00:10:48,439 --> 00:10:51,233
It's perfect for like heavy IO workloads.

197
00:10:51,233 --> 00:10:53,110
This is great.

198
00:10:54,320 --> 00:10:56,739
It it does add some complexity

199
00:10:56,739 --> 00:10:59,742
with race conditions and deadlocks
that you have to handle.

200
00:11:01,911 --> 00:11:03,162
If you have unbounded

201
00:11:03,162 --> 00:11:06,165
goroutines, it can cause a lot of memory,

202
00:11:06,248 --> 00:11:09,251
leaks that you need to watch out for.

203
00:11:10,586 --> 00:11:14,340
And always make sure that you're
propagating any context to downstream

204
00:11:14,340 --> 00:11:14,757
calls.

205
00:11:14,757 --> 00:11:18,135
If you've got goroutines
that call go routines, a call routines,

206
00:11:18,469 --> 00:11:24,058
you want to propagate those context, down
so that, when a cancellation happens,

207
00:11:24,058 --> 00:11:27,353
that I'm canceling all of the go,
routines that are happening.

208
00:11:27,978 --> 00:11:31,023
And remember,
not every flow needs that concurrency.

209
00:11:31,357 --> 00:11:35,194
Sequential logic is a whole lot simpler
to debug than running,

210
00:11:35,194 --> 00:11:40,574
you know, concurrent, items,
that, aggregating the results back.

211
00:11:40,908 --> 00:11:41,158
All right.

212
00:11:41,158 --> 00:11:45,287
So only use concurrency
when there's a true benefit there.

213
00:11:45,621 --> 00:11:49,291
And then also if I've got channels
that are out there that are running

214
00:11:49,291 --> 00:11:53,838
without timeouts or shutdowns,
they can sit and block forever, right?

215
00:11:53,838 --> 00:11:57,049
Waiting for that channel
to fill up before I move on.

216
00:11:57,049 --> 00:12:01,053
So make sure that you set 
some of those timeouts and shutdown paths.

217
00:12:01,762 --> 00:12:02,304
All right.

218
00:12:02,304 --> 00:12:04,098
So go concurrency.

219
00:12:04,098 --> 00:12:06,517
It's a practical way of scaling IO.

220
00:12:06,517 --> 00:12:10,730
Channel and worker pools
provide explicit control over,

221
00:12:10,730 --> 00:12:14,817
those how that concurrency
in those go routines.

222
00:12:15,109 --> 00:12:18,028
And then make sure that you, have bounded
concurrency

223
00:12:18,028 --> 00:12:21,741
plus cancellation
to keep your services stable.

224
00:12:22,074 --> 00:12:24,702
If you don't do that,
you can chew up a lot of resources

225
00:12:24,702 --> 00:12:28,122
and have some instability
in your microservices.
